{"title_page": "Salesian Oblates of the Sacred Heart of Jesus", "text_new": "'''Salesian Oblates of the Sacred Heart of Jesus''' (in Italian ''Salesiane Oblate del Sacro Cuore di Ges\u00f9'' with the abbreviation S.O.S.C.<ref name=\"AP07\">''Ann. Pont. 2007'', p. 1686.</ref>) is an institute of religious sisters of pontifical right of Italian origen founded by [[Salesian]] Bishop Mgr. [[Giuseppe Cognata]] in [[1933]] at [[Bova Marina]], [[Italy]]. The institute belongs to the [[Don Bosco|Salesian Family]].\n\n== History ==\n\nThe institute was founded on December 8, 1933 in [[Bova Marina]] by Mgr. Cognata, Bishop of the Diocesis of Bova (1933-1940).<ref name=\"DIP\">DIP, vol. VIII ([[1988]]), coll. 387-388, voce a cura di G. Rocca.</ref> It was approved as institute of [[pontifical right]] on January 16, 1962 and it was recognized by the Italian State on December 26, 1962. The [[Holy See]] gave to it the [[decretum laudis|decree of praise]] on January 24, 1972;<ref name=\"DIP\"/> appartiene alla [[famiglia salesiana]] dal 24 dicembre [[1983]].<ref>SDB Org, 2008. Groups of the Salesian Family. Link retrived on March 12, 2008 from http://www.sdb.org/ITA/Pagine/_1_21_46_1_.htm#8</ref>\n\n== Activities and expansion ==\n\nThe Salesian Oblates are dedicated to Christian education of the youth: they have kindergartents, schools, youth centres (oratories) and pastoral centers.<ref name=\"DIP\"/>\n\nBesides Italy, their original country, they have communities in [[Bolivia]] and [[Peru]]:<ref>SOSC, 2005. Elenco Case. Link retrieved on July 29, 2013 from http://www.salesianesosc.org/1/elenco_case_675266.html<ref name=\"AP07\"/>\n\n== Bibliografy ==\n\n* ''Annuario Pontificio per l'anno 2007'', [[Libreria Editrice Vaticana]], [[Citt\u00e0 del Vaticano]] 2007. {{ISBN|978-88-209-7908-9}}.\n* Guerrino Pelliccia e Giancarlo Rocca (curr.), ''Dizionario degli Istituti di Perfezione'' (10 voll.),  Edizioni paoline, [[Milano]] 1974\u20132003.\n\n== Collegamenti esterni ==\n\n* [http://www.salesianesosc.org/ Official website of the Salesian Oblates of the Sacred Heart of Jesus.]\n\n== References ==\n\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Salesian Order]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1933]]\n[[Category:Catholic female orders and societies]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic religious sisters and nuns]]\n[[Category:1933 establishments in Italy]]\n", "text_old": "'''Salesian Oblates of the Sacred Heart of Jesus''' (in Italian ''Salesiane Oblate del Sacro Cuore di Ges\u00f9'' with the abbreviation S.O.S.C.<ref name=\"AP07\">''Ann. Pont. 2007'', p. 1686.</ref>) is an institute of religious sisters of pontifical right of Italian origen founded by [[Salesian]] Bishop Mgr. [[Giuseppe Cognata]] in [[1933]] at [[Bova Marina]], [[Italy]]. The institute belongs to the [[Don Bosco|Salesian Family]].\n\n== History ==\n\nThe institute was founded on December 8, 1933 in [[Bova Marina]] by Mgr. Cognata, Bishop of the Diocesis of Bova (1933-1940).<ref name=\"DIP\">DIP, vol. VIII ([[1988]]), coll. 387-388, voce a cura di G. Rocca.</ref> It was approved as institute of [[pontifical right]] on January 16, 1962 and it was recognized by the Italian State on December 26, 1962. The [[Holy See]] gave to it the [[decretum laudis|decree of praise]] on January 24, 1972;<ref name=\"DIP\"/> appartiene alla [[famiglia salesiana]] dal 24 dicembre [[1983]].<ref>SDB Org, 2008. Groups of the Salesian Family. Link retrived on March 12, 2008 from http://www.sdb.org/ITA/Pagine/_1_21_46_1_.htm#8</ref>\n\n== Activities and expansion ==\n\nThe Salesian Oblates are dedicated to Christian education of the youth: they have kindergartents, schools, youth centres (oratories) and pastoral centers.<ref name=\"DIP\"/>\n\nBesides Italy, their original country, they have communities in [[Bolivia]] and [[Peru]]:<ref>SOSC, 2005. Elenco Case. Link retrieved on July 29, 2013 from http://www.salesianesosc.org/1/elenco_case_675266.html<ref name=\"AP07\"/>\n\n== Bibliografy ==\n\n* ''Annuario Pontificio per l'anno 2007'', [[Libreria Editrice Vaticana]], [[Citt\u00e0 del Vaticano]] 2007. {{ISBN|978-88-209-7908-9}}.\n* Guerrino Pelliccia e Giancarlo Rocca (curr.), ''Dizionario degli Istituti di Perfezione'' (10 voll.),  Edizioni paoline, [[Milano]] 1974-2003.\n\n== Collegamenti esterni ==\n\n* [http://www.salesianesosc.org/ Official website of the Salesian Oblates of the Sacred Heart of Jesus.]\n\n== References ==\n\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Salesian Order]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1933]]\n[[Category:Catholic female orders and societies]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic religious sisters and nuns]]\n[[Category:1933 establishments in Italy]]\n", "name_user": "Amkgp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBibliografy:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1974-2003 \u2192 1974\u20132003", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salesian_Oblates_of_the_Sacred_Heart_of_Jesus"}
{"title_page": "Terhemba Shija", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| image        = File:Shija.jpg\n| image_size   = 150px\n| honorific-prefix    = Professor\n| name         = Terhemba Shija\n| caption      =\n| birth_name   = Terhemba Shija\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1960|11|23|df=y}}\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| death_cause  =\n| birth_place  = [[Vandeikya]], [[Benue State]] [[Nigeria]]\n| nationality  = Nigerian\n| education    = Bristow Secondary School Gboko\n| alma mater   = [[University of Calabar]] <br> [[University of Maiduguri]] <br>[[Benue State University]] Makurdi\n| Profession   = teacher, writer, politician \n| spouse       =  Hon. Justice Theresa Mimi Shija\n| residence    = \n| parents      = \n| children     = Torkuma Begha Shija <br> Vershima Gafa Shija\n| relatives    = \n| website      = \n}}\n'''Terhemba Shija''' (born 23 November 1960) is a Nigerian academic, writer, politician and philanthropist who currently lectures at the [[Nasarawa State University]], Keffi. He is of [[Tiv]] extraction and hails from [[Vandeikya]] local government Area in the North-East Senatorial District of [[Benue State]] in central [[Nigeria]].<ref name = \"https://allafrica.com/stories/201411030768.html\">{{cite web|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201411030768.html|publisher=allafrica.com/stories/201411030768.html|title=Nigeria: PDP Guber Aspirant Decries Costly Nomination Forms|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref> Shija garnered political prominence when he served as a Member of the 3rd National Assembly of [[House of Representatives of Nigeria]], [[Abuja]] between 1992\u20131993 and later headed two separate ministries as Commissioner of Information and Culture as well as Commissioner of Local Government and Chieftaincy Affairs Benue State between 1999\u20132002, during the administration of Governor [[George Akume]].<ref name = \"https://thenationonlineng.net/just-in-ex-reps-member-shija-dumps-pdp-may-join-apc/\">{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/just-in-ex-reps-member-shija-dumps-pdp-may-join-apc/|title=JUST IN: Ex-Reps member Shija dumps PDP, may join APC|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref name = \"https://allafrica.com/stories/200212240066.html\">{{cite web|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/200212240066.html|publisher=allafrica.com/stories/200212240066.html|title=Nigeria: Assembly Approves 4 Commissioners|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe aspired to contest for the seat of the Governor of Benue State in the 2015 General Elections on the platform of the [[People's Democratic Party]] but failed to secure the party's ticket at the primaries due to the party's zoning system not favoring him. Shija also served as the Director General of Dankwambo Campaign Organisation in support of His Excellency, Dr. [[Ibrahim Hassan Dankwambo]] a former Governor of [[Gombe State]] who aspired to run for the Office of the President of Nigeria on the platform of a simimlar political Party but lost the party's ticket to Alhaji [[Atiku Abubakar]].<ref name=\"https://allafrica.com/stories/201411030768.html\"/><ref name = \"https://guardian.ng/news/gombe-governor-declares-for-presidency/\">{{cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/news/gombe-governor-declares-for-presidency/|title=Gombe governor declares for presidency|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWidely regarded as one of the gifted writers of his generation, Shija has a large number of publications both in local and international journals and has authored several books which have received critical acclaim.\n\n== Early life ==\nShija attended W.M Bristow Secondary School Gboko between 1973\u20131977 and obtained his West African School Certificate WASC (Division Two) before proceeding to the University of Calabar where he earned a Bachelor of Arts, B.A. (Hons)Second Class Upper Division in 1985. In 1988, he studied and obtained his Master of Arts, M.A. (English) in Creative Writing from the University of Maiduguri. Shija would later earn a doctorate in African Literature from the Benue State University Makurdi in 2005.\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image        = File:Shija.jpg\n| image_size   = 150px\n| honorific-prefix    = Professor\n| name         = Terhemba Shija\n| caption      =\n| birth_name   = Terhemba Shija\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1960|11|23|df=y}}\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| death_cause  =\n| birth_place  = [[Vandeikya]], [[Benue State]] [[Nigeria]]\n| nationality  = Nigerian\n| education    = Bristow Secondary School Gboko\n| alma mater   = [[University of Calabar]] <br> [[University of Maiduguri]] <br>[[Benue State University]] Makurdi\n| Profession   = teacher, writer, politician \n| spouse       =  Hon. Justice Theresa Mimi Shija\n| residence    = \n| parents      = \n| children     = Torkuma Begha Shija <br> Vershima Gafa Shija\n| relatives    = \n| website      = \n}}\n'''Terhemba Shija''' (born 23 November 1960) is a Nigerian academic, writer, politician and philanthropist who currently lectures at the [[Nasarawa State University]], Keffi. He is of [[Tiv]] extraction and hails from [[Vandeikya]] local government Area in the North-East Senatorial District of [[Benue State]] in central [[Nigeria]].<ref name = \"https://allafrica.com/stories/201411030768.html\">{{cite web|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201411030768.html|publisher=allafrica.com/stories/201411030768.html|title=Nigeria: PDP Guber Aspirant Decries Costly Nomination Forms|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref> Shija garnered political prominence when he served as a Member of the 3rd National Assembly of [[House of Representatives of Nigeria]], [[Abuja]] between 1992-1993 and later headed two separate ministries as Commissioner of Information and Culture as well as Commissioner of Local Government and Chieftaincy Affairs Benue State between 1999-2002, during the administration of Governor [[George Akume]].<ref name = \"https://thenationonlineng.net/just-in-ex-reps-member-shija-dumps-pdp-may-join-apc/\">{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/just-in-ex-reps-member-shija-dumps-pdp-may-join-apc/|title=JUST IN: Ex-Reps member Shija dumps PDP, may join APC|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref name = \"https://allafrica.com/stories/200212240066.html\">{{cite web|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/200212240066.html|publisher=allafrica.com/stories/200212240066.html|title=Nigeria: Assembly Approves 4 Commissioners|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n\nHe aspired to contest for the seat of the Governor of Benue State in the 2015 General Elections on the platform of the [[People's Democratic Party]] but failed to secure the party's ticket at the primaries due to the party's zoning system not favoring him. Shija also served as the Director General of Dankwambo Campaign Organisation in support of His Excellency, Dr. [[Ibrahim Hassan Dankwambo]] a former Governor of [[Gombe State]] who aspired to run for the Office of the President of Nigeria on the platform of a simimlar political Party but lost the party's ticket to Alhaji [[Atiku Abubakar]].<ref name = \"https://allafrica.com/stories/201411030768.html\">{{cite web|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201411030768.html|publisher=allafrica.com/stories/201411030768.html|title=Nigeria: PDP Guber Aspirant Decries Costly Nomination Forms|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref name = \"https://guardian.ng/news/gombe-governor-declares-for-presidency/\">{{cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/news/gombe-governor-declares-for-presidency/|title=Gombe governor declares for presidency|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n\nWidely regarded as one of the gifted writers of his generation, Shija has a large number of publications both in local and international journals and has authored several books which have received critical acclaim. \n\n== Early Life ==\nShija attended W.M Bristow Secondary School Gboko between 1973-1977 and obtained his West African School Certificate WASC (Division Two) before proceeding to the University of Calabar where he earned a Bachelor of Arts, B.A. (Hons)Second Class Upper Division in 1985. In 1988, he studied and obtained his Master of Arts, M.A. (English) in Creative Writing from the University of of Maiduguri. Shija would later earn a doctorate in African Literature from the Benue State University Makurdi in 2005. \n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n", "name_user": "Amkgp", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, addedorphantag,typo(s) fixed: of of \u2192 of", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terhemba_Shija"}
